Methods Overview

The goal was to generate predictive spatial models for four simulated genotypes of
Setaria: wildtype, high anthocyanin content, dwarf, and increased leaf temperature. We used PEcAn to generate ED2 runs at 29 southeast US sites in 3 ecosystems at each site: mixed forest, pine forest, and prairie. We utilized PEcAns sensitivity analysis to simulate the 4 genotypes. The median run was used as wildtype, -1 SD for quantum efficiency represented high anthocyanin content, -1 SD for stomatal slope represented the increased leaf temperature genotype, and +1 SD for fine root to leaf ratio represented the dwarf genotype. We used only the final year of the 10 year simulations as data, averaging the NPP over the summer months (June, July, and August) as a response variable. We downloaded weather data for each site from Daymet using the daymetr package (Hufkens et al. 2018) and calculated 19 bioclimatic variables using the dismo package (Hijmans et al. 2022). The resulting dataset contained mean summer NPP, the site ID, the 19 bioclimatic variables, mean solar radiation, and mean vapor pressure deficit, ecosystem, and genotype. Data preparation, model training, model validation, and prediction were facilitated by the packages in the tidymodels ecosystem (Kuhn and Wickham 2020). The dataset was split 80/20 into a training and test set using the rsample package (Frick et al. 2022) and prepared for modeling using the recipes package (Kuhn et al. 2023) (steps detailed below). We compared two candidate models, a random forest model (using the ranger engine), and a LASSO regression (using the glmnet engine) (Friedman et al. 2010, Wright and Ziegler 2017). We compared the predictive ability of the candidate models using 10-fold cross-validation RMSE and \(R^2\) values.

A grid of points every 0.5 was generated within the bounds of the Southeastern US states that the ED2 simulations were sampled from using the terra, stars, and sf packages (Pebesma 2018, Hijmans 2023, Pebesma and Bivand 2023).

Data Prep

rf_recipe
## 
##  Recipe 
## 
##  Inputs
## Number of variables by role
## outcome:    1
## predictor: 23
## id:         1
## 
##  Training information
## Training data contained 246 data points and no incomplete rows.
## 
##  Operations
##  Centering and scaling for: bio1, bio2, bio3, bio4, bio5, bio6, ... | Trained
##  Interactions with: genotype:ecosystem | Trained
##  Dummy variables from: genotype, ecosystem | Trained
##  Zero variance filter removed: <none> | Trained
##  PCA extraction with: bio1, bio2, bio3, bio4, bio5, bio6, bio7, ... | Trained

All numeric predictors (the 19 bioclim variables, mean daylight, and mean vapor pressure deficit) are centered and scaled, dummy variables are created for genotype, ecosystem, and their interaction, and PCA is performed on the bioclim variables to retain a number of components that explains 85% of variance.

Model Validation

I fit two models using the same data recipe, a random forest model and a LASSO regression and performed 10-fold cross validation. Random forest outperformed LASSO regression.

bind_rows("random forest" = rf_cv, "LASSO regression" = lm_cv, .id = "model") |> 
  dplyr::select(model, .metric, mean) |> 
  pivot_wider(values_from = mean, names_from = .metric)
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   model             rmse   rsq
##   <chr>            <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 random forest    0.143 0.978
## 2 LASSO regression 0.452 0.845
(rf_pred_plot + labs(title = "Random forest")) /
  (lm_pred_plot + labs(title = "LASSO regression")) + plot_layout(guides = "collect")

Spatial predictions

I generated a grid of points to predict summer average NPP after 10 years of growth at.

tar_load(c(seus, grid_data))
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = seus) +
  geom_point(data = grid_data, aes(x = lon, y = lat))

Grid of points 0.5 apart used for predicting mean summer NPP
